Goal - Build and deploy a production-ready URL shortener with authentication, analytics, and cloud deployment.

Core Requirements

Frontend (EJS)
Build full UI using EJS (server-side rendering)
Pages required:
Home (URL shortening form)
Login and Signup
Dashboard (user URLs and analytics)
Implement conditional rendering for guest vs logged-in users
Keep UI simple and clean (basic CSS or Bootstrap is fine)
Authentication System
Implement signup, login, and logout
Use bcrypt to hash passwords
Use session-based authentication (express-session)
Store user data securely in MongoDB

Security requirements:

Never store plain text passwords
Validate inputs (email format, password strength)
Store secrets in environment variables
Guest Mode
Allow users to shorten URLs without logging in
Store guest URLs using session or a database flag (isGuest)
Optional: allow guest URLs to be linked to account after login
URL Logic
Generate unique short IDs (e.g., nanoid)
Redirect users to original URL
Prevent duplicates:
If the same user shortens the same URL, return the existing short URL
Track usage:
Click count
Visit timestamps
Dashboard Features
Display all URLs created by the user
Show total clicks per URL
Show creation date
Optional: sorting and filtering
Logging
Log incoming requests
Log errors
Log redirect activity
Use morgan for basic logging or winston for more advanced logging
Deployment Plan

Step 1 (Learning phase):

Deploy backend on AWS EC2
Use MongoDB Atlas for database
Optional: configure Nginx

Step 2 (Final deployment):

Deploy on a free platform like Render or Railway
Add live project link to resume
Google Authentication (Optional)
Implement OAuth using Passport.js
Safe if done correctly:
Use official Google OAuth flow
Do not store passwords from Google
Store only basic profile info (email, name, googleId)
MongoDB Safety Checklist
Hash passwords using bcrypt
Use environment variables for DB connection and secrets
Restrict database access using IP whitelist (MongoDB Atlas)
Create index on shortId for performance and uniqueness
CORS
Not required if using EJS with same backend
Only needed if frontend and backend are separate

Additional Important Tasks

Performance and Scalability

Add index on shortId
Consider caching (optional, e.g., Redis for advanced setup)

Security Enhancements

Add rate limiting to prevent abuse
Use helmet for secure HTTP headers
Sanitize inputs to prevent injection attacks

Validation

Validate URLs before storing them
Handle invalid inputs properly

Expiry Feature (Optional)

Allow links to expire after a certain time

Project Structure

Organize code into folders such as controllers, models, routes, middlewares, views, and utilities

logs should be cleaned upp after 15 days or 1 mb

proper error handling

README (Very Important)
Include:

Project description
Features
Tech stack
Live link
Screenshots
Setup instructions


